                        "type": "link",
                        "name": "Pathfinder #149: Against the Scarlet Triad pg. 89",
                        "alt": "Pathfinder #149: Against the Scarlet Triad pg. 89",
                        "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq02065"
                    },
                    "page": 89
                }
            ],
            "html": "The largest solifugids, duneshakers, are so immense that their movements make the terrain around them tremble. They can prey on creatures the size of mammoths or even larger.<br/><br/><b><u><a aonid=\"5\" game-obj=\"Skills\" general=\"true\">Recall Knowledge - Animal</a></u> (<u><a aonid=\"10\" game-obj=\"Skills\">Nature</a></u>)</b>: DC 38"
        },
        {
            "name": "Solifugid",
            "type": "section",
            "sections": [
                {
                    "name": "Solifugid Burrows",
                    "type": "section",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Pathfinder #149: Against the Scarlet Triad",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Pathfinder #149: Against the Scarlet Triad pg. 89",
                                "alt": "Pathfinder #149: Against the Scarlet Triad pg. 89",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq02065"
                            },
                            "page": 89
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "additional_lore",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Additional Lore",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Additional Lore",
                        "image": "Sidebar_2_AdditionalLore.png"
                    },
                    "html": "Most species of solifugid lay their eggs in burrows. The female doesn\u2019t eat while guarding her eggs, and thus fights even more aggressively against any creatures she deems potential threats to her brood. The bodies of wayward adventurers often litter such burrows, though the risks of exploring such treasure-laden nests often deter fortune-hunters from trying their luck with such caches."
                },
                {
                    "name": "Solifugid Burrows",
                    "type": "section",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Pathfinder #149: Against the Scarlet Triad",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Pathfinder #149: Against the Scarlet Triad pg. 89",
                                "alt": "Pathfinder #149: Against the Scarlet Triad pg. 89",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq02065"
                            },
                            "page": 89
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "locations",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Locations",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Locations",
                        "image": "Sidebar_3_Locations.png"
                    },
                    "html": "Most species of solifugid lay their eggs in burrows. The female doesn't eat while guarding her eggs, and thus fights even more aggressively against any creatures she deems potential threats to her brood. The bodies of wayward adventurers often litter such burrows, though this does little to deter other fortune-hunters from trying their luck in such treasure-laden nests."
                }
            ],
            "sources": [
                {
                    "type": "source",
                    "name": "Pathfinder #149: Against the Scarlet Triad",
                    "link": {
                        "type": "link",
                        "name": "Pathfinder #149: Against the Scarlet Triad pg. 89",
                        "alt": "Pathfinder #149: Against the Scarlet Triad pg. 89",
                        "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq02065"
                    },
                    "page": 89
                }
            ],
            "html": "Giant solifugids are monstrous vermin with six legs and two large feeding appendages easily mistaken for an additional pair of legs. They are often called camel spiders, sun spiders, or wind scorpions, despite the fact that they are neither spiders nor scorpions."
        }
    ],
